ught about Vimy Ridge. But that celebrated victory was just one battle among many to shape the country’s experience of the First World War. Portraits of Battle brings together biography, battle accounts, and historiographical analysis to examine the lives of a cross-section of Canadians who served in the war. Contributors to this thoughtful collection consider the range of Canadians touched by war – soldiers and their loved ones, deserters, nurses, Indigenous people, those injured in body or mind – raising fundamental questions about the nature of conflict and memory. These portraits of the formerly faceless men and women honoured on war memorials fill in what is often missing from accounts of the Great War. In the process, they provide a more nuanced perspective on the complex legacy of that war in Canadian history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zCanadavBiography. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh1 aBroad, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aComacchio, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalcon, Kyle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrugia, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrugia, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGlassford, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHabkirk, Evan J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHabklrk, Evan J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeath, Gordon L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIacobelli, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov